TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Theory of Urban Growth
AU  - Black, Duncan
AU  - Henderson, Vernon
Y1  - 1999/04/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250060
DO  - 10.1086/250060
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 252
EP  - 284
VL  - 107
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In an economy experiencing endogenous economic growth and exogenous population growth, we explore two main themes: how urbanization affects efficiency of the growth process and how growth affects patterns of urbanization. Localized information spillovers promote agglomeration and human capital accumulation and fosters endogenous growth. Individual city sizes grow with local human capital accumulation and knowledge spillovers; and city with empirical evidence. We analyze whether local governments can successfully internalize local dynamic externalities. In addition, we explore how growth involves real income differences across city types and how urbanization can foster income inequality.
AB  - In an economy experiencing endogenous economic growth and exogenous population growth, we explore two main themes: how urbanization affects efficiency of the growth process and how growth affects patterns of urbanization. Localized information spillovers promote agglomeration and human capital accumulation and fosters endogenous growth. Individual city sizes grow with local human capital accumulation and knowledge spillovers; and city with empirical evidence. We analyze whether local governments can successfully internalize local dynamic externalities. In addition, we explore how growth involves real income differences across city types and how urbanization can foster income inequality.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250060
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250060
Y2  - 2024/03/22
